Russian Communism Makes a Comeback
Moscow—More than a year ago, when I returned to my hometown of Moscow on sabbatical from an American university,
my destination was not a bastion of free speech.
But here, there still used to be some freedom.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny toured the country to win support for candidates who were not under Kremlin control.
Protests have erupted among the populace.
Independent NGOs operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts are not necessarily in line with the Kremlin's direction.
And the Communists are widely regarded as relics of history.
Since then, Navalny has been incarcerated, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved for being "extremist," and its members are either exiled or under investigation.
Nearly every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agent" list — and worse — labeled as "unwelcome persons."
Last year, Russia slipped into a non-free status, though not far off, but very acutely.
For example, in 2012, a law was passed to designate foreign agents, aimed at undermining or disparaging institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" and receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where retweeting a tweet can now be grounds for labeling someone a foreign agent.
（ "Unpopular" labels can lead to complete bans.
) This year alone, there were record-breaking additions of 101 entities to the foreign agent list.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of news and propaganda work is naturally to influence politics.
And that is precisely the problem: While Russian President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he has come to view criticism as a survival threat.
尽管遭受了这一切沉默与迫害，最终能够生存下来并在克里姆林宫内成为唯一的真正反对派的，竟然是一支不太可能的共产党组织。
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — encouraging people to vote for those most likely to defeat the pro-Kremlin candidates — which saw the Communists perform strongly in both last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), compared to nearly 49.8% for the United Russia party backed by the Kremlin.
但共产党人拒绝接受这一结果，坚称投票结果被操纵。
Fact is, some experts estimate that they should have garnered about 30% of the vote, while United Russia should have had around 35%.
To many Russians, the Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original Communists.
Not only do they not deny earthly pleasures; indeed, party members wear fur coats, are avid travelers abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are multimillionaires – such as charismatic Agrarian chief Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's elections).
Despite being led by 77-year-old Vyacheslav久加诺夫，the party is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Nikolai Bondarenko is one example.
Known as "Red Navalny," the 36-year-old Bondarenko severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform in 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister suggested that Russians should be able to eat better on a mere monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove him wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite threats to ban him from running, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in last month's State Duma elections.
Although he received support from Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the United Russia Party's candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a slogan for a protest, accusing "the state and government takeover" of United Russia.
Then there is Anastasia Yudasyova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she inexplicably lost the previous election.
But she is still very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Engelicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Perversely, the Communist Party’s modernization reflects a longing for the past: In 1917, Lenin’s Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although that state, though strict, was not without its fairness and kindness.
Like Navalny on the liberal side, today’s Communists represent a predictable and consistent vision under which one person’s whims do not affect everyone else.
This logic has led to more and more opponents of the Kremlin uniting: a coalition that can be called "United Russia" to challenge Putin.
This is not limited to Russia alone.
<s>In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš – also known as the Czech Donald Trump – failed to continue as prime minister, as opposition alliances put aside their ideological differences and formed a common coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition alliance.
<s>As Fiala put it, "People have had enough of populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
<s>The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified electoral list and run a single candidate for prime minister in next year's parliamentary elections.
<s>Naturally, the Czech Republic still has a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
<s>Overthrowing Putin, however, will be much more difficult, and one can expect even more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party.
But this approach also poses risks to the Kremlin.
Currently, the president claims that Russian democracy "is not dead," and points to the presence of "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he at least remains interested in pretending that Russia has not been heading towards near-totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia towards more turbulence.
If the Kremlin were as fickle in making and enforcing rules as it was with Russian liberals, driving the Communists underground, a societal explosion would be more likely.
And if it decides to no longer suppress it, the Russian Communists – yes, Communists – could become a force to be reckoned with.
